President Uhuru Kenyatta’s decision to reward Kenyan athletes who excelled in Tokyo is most laudable. The athletes, once again, put our country on the global map by being at position 19 worldwide and one in Africa.  But while celebrating these winners, there is one man who lost in Tokyo who also needs to be honoured: Ferdinand Omanyala Omurwa.  Barely two weeks after making history by becoming the first Kenyan to qualify for the 100m semi-finals in a time of 10.01 seconds, he went on to lower the time to 9.86 seconds in Austria. He doubtless has a great future.  Help us serve you better by completing our quick survey. Omanyala, just like javelin champion Julius Yego has proven than Kenya has great potential in other sporting fields besides mid and long distance races.  President Uhuru rewards triumphant 2020 Tokyo Olympics team  How 9.86 seconds have changed Ferdinand Omanyala’s life  Omanyala sets new 100m national record in Austria   Our athletics stars deserve more respect and State care Such emerging athletes deserve our full support. The secret to topping in the Olympics lies in diversifying our sporting menu.   How CORD MPs planned to disrupt President Uhuru Kenyatta's address to the nation  Wakenya watoa maoni kuhusu Mwaka mpya ya 2016  2014 KASS MARATHON: Athletes win big in Kass Marathon By Editorial | 17 seconds ago By Editorial | 1 day ago By Editorial | 2 days ago By Editorial | 3 days ago